AB  - It is almost always possible to find some fault with any published article. It might be argued, for example, that Donald Sternitzke's article, “The Great American Competitive Disadvantage: Fact or Fiction” (JIBS, Fall 1979, pp. 25–36) could be improved by performing sensitivity tests on various definitions given to the overall region and on the degree of aggregation employed in the establishment of commodity classes. Tests by others have shown that such variations in definitions have yielded significantly different results.1
